",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"p\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"© \\\",2026,\\\" Abdihamid Moallim\\\"]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"flex items-center gap-4\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"a\\\",\\\"LinkedIn\\\",{\\\"href\\\":\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/abmoallim/\\\",\\\"target\\\":\\\"_blank\\\",\\\"rel\\\":\\\"noopener noreferrer\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"transition-colors hover:text-clay\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"LinkedIn\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"a\\\",\\\"GitHub\\\",{\\\"href\\\":\\\"https://github.com/abmoallim\\\",\\\"target\\\":\\\"_blank\\\",\\\"rel\\\":\\\"noopener noreferrer\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"transition-colors hover:text-clay\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"GitHub\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"a\\\",\\\"X\\\",{\\\"href\\\":\\\"https://x.com/abmoallim\\\",\\\"target\\\":\\\"_blank\\\",\\\"rel\\\":\\\"noopener noreferrer\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"transition-colors hover:text-clay\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"X\\\"}]]}]]}]}]]}]]}]]}]],null],null],\\\"couldBeIntercepted\\\":false,\\\"initialHead\\\":[null,\\\"$Ld\\\"],\\\"globalErrorComponent\\\":\\\"$e\\\",\\\"missingSlots\\\":\\\"$Wf\\\"}]\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"10:I[2972,[\\\"972\\\",\\\"static/chunks/972-0fea25be27918f94.js\\\",\\\"308\\\",\\\"static/chunks/app/blog/%5Bslug%5D/page-509dcbc32cb4be24.js\\\"],\\\"\\\"]\\n11:T1785,\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cimg src=\\\"/imgs/web-scraping.png\\\" alt=\\\"alt text\\\"\\u003e\\nWeb scraping is an essential technique in a developer's toolkit, allowing the extraction of data from websites for various purposes, such as data analysis, monitoring, and automation. Playwright, paired with Node.js, provides a powerful and flexible framework for web scraping, especially when dealing with modern, dynamic websites. In this tutorial, we'll walk you through setting up a web scraping project with Playwright and cover essential aspects of scraping, from basic setups to handling more complex scenarios.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e1. Setting Up Your Environment\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eTo begin, you'll need to have Node.js installed on your machine. Node.js is a JavaScript runtime that allows you to run JavaScript code outside of a web browser. Once you have Node.js installed, you can create a new project directory and initialize a Node.js project:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cpre\\u003e\\u003ccode class=\\\"language-bash\\\"\\u003emkdir playwright-scraper\\ncd playwright-scraper\\nnpm init -y\\nnpm install playwright\\n\\u003c/code\\u003e\\u003c/pre\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe commands above will create a new directory, initialize a Node.js project, and install Playwright. Playwright is a Node.js library to automate Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit with a single API. It is ideal for scraping tasks because of its ability to handle complex web interactions, including those involving JavaScript and dynamic content.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e2. Writing Your First Playwright Script\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eLet's start by writing a simple script that launches a browser, navigates to a webpage, and retrieves the page title. Create a new file named \\u003ccode\\u003escraper.js\\u003c/code\\u003e and add the following code:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cpre\\u003e\\u003ccode class=\\\"language-javascript\\\"\\u003econst { chromium } = require('playwright');\\n\\n(async () =\\u003e {\\n  const browser = await chromium.launch();\\n  const page = await browser.newPage();\\n  await page.goto('https://example.com');\\n  const title = await page.title();\\n  console.log(`Title: ${title}`);\\n  await browser.close();\\n})();\\n\\u003c/code\\u003e\\u003c/pre\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIn this script, we use Playwright to launch a Chromium browser, open a new page, navigate to \\\"\\u003ca href=\\\"https://example.com\\\"\\u003ehttps://example.com\\u003c/a\\u003e\\\", and print the page's title to the console. Finally, the browser is closed. This is a basic example, but it showcases the simplicity and power of Playwright for web scraping.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e3. Extracting Data from a Web Page\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWeb scraping often involves extracting specific pieces of data from a webpage. Let's modify our script to extract the headlines from the Hacker News homepage. Update your \\u003ccode\\u003escraper.js\\u003c/code\\u003e file with the following code:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cpre\\u003e\\u003ccode class=\\\"language-javascript\\\"\\u003eawait page.goto('https://news.ycombinator.com/');\\nconst headlines = await page.$$eval('.storylink', links =\\u003e links.map(link =\\u003e link.textContent));\\nconsole.log(headlines);\\n\\u003c/code\\u003e\\u003c/pre\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHere, we're using the \\u003ccode\\u003e$$eval\\u003c/code\\u003e function, which allows us to select all elements matching a CSS selector (\\u003ccode\\u003e.storylink\\u003c/code\\u003e in this case) and run a function on them. The function extracts the text content of each element and returns it as an array of strings.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e4. Handling Dynamic Content\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eModern websites often load content dynamically using JavaScript, which means that the content may not be available immediately when the page loads. Playwright's \\u003ccode\\u003ewaitForSelector\\u003c/code\\u003e method can be used to wait for specific elements to appear before interacting with them:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cpre\\u003e\\u003ccode class=\\\"language-javascript\\\"\\u003eawait page.goto('https://example.com');\\nawait page.waitForSelector('.dynamic-content');\\nconst content = await page.$eval('.dynamic-content', el =\\u003e el.textContent);\\nconsole.log(content);\\n\\u003c/code\\u003e\\u003c/pre\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIn this example, we wait for an element with the class \\u003ccode\\u003e.dynamic-content\\u003c/code\\u003e to appear on the page before extracting its text content.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e5. Managing Authentication\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eSome websites require users to log in before accessing certain data. Playwright can handle this by filling out login forms and submitting them:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cpre\\u003e\\u003ccode class=\\\"language-javascript\\\"\\u003eawait page.goto('https://example.com/login');\\nawait page.fill('#username', 'yourUsername');\\nawait page.fill('#password', 'yourPassword');\\nawait page.click('#loginButton');\\n\\u003c/code\\u003e\\u003c/pre\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThis script navigates to a login page, fills out the username and password fields, and clicks the login button. Playwright will manage the session automatically, allowing you to scrape protected content.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e6. Saving Scraped Data\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eOnce you've extracted data from a webpage, you'll often want to save it for later use. You can save data to a JSON file using Node.js's built-in \\u003ccode\\u003efs\\u003c/code\\u003e module:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cpre\\u003e\\u003ccode class=\\\"language-javascript\\\"\\u003econst fs = require('fs');\\nfs.writeFileSync('headlines.json', JSON.stringify(headlines, null, 2));\\n\\u003c/code\\u003e\\u003c/pre\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThis code saves the \\u003ccode\\u003eheadlines\\u003c/code\\u003e array to a file named \\u003ccode\\u003eheadlines.json\\u003c/code\\u003e, formatting the JSON with an indentation of 2 spaces.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003e7. Best Practices for Web Scraping\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWhen scraping websites, it's important to follow best practices to avoid legal issues or being blocked by the website. Here are some tips:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eRespect \\u003ccode\\u003erobots.txt\\u003c/code\\u003e:\\u003c/strong\\u003e Always check the site's \\u003ccode\\u003erobots.txt\\u003c/code\\u003e file to see what parts of the site you're allowed to scrape.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eRate Limiting:\\u003c/strong\\u003e Introduce delays between requests to avoid overwhelming the server.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eError Handling:\\u003c/strong\\u003e Implement error handling to manage issues such as network errors or unexpected changes in the webpage structure.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eConclusion\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWeb scraping with Playwright and Node.js offers a powerful way to collect data from websites, whether they are static or dynamically loaded. With the basics covered in this tutorial, you should be well-equipped to start building your own web scrapers. From handling simple HTML pages to complex, JavaScript-heavy sites requiring authentication, Playwright provides the tools you need to get the job done efficiently.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHappy scraping!\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"7:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"main\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-6 px-4 pb-8 pt-10 sm:px-6\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L10\\\",null,{\\\"href\\\":\\\"/blog\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"inline-block font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-ink/50 transition-colors hover:text-clay\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"← Back to writing\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-ink/40\\\",\\\"children\\\":[\\\"2024-08-24\\\",\\\" · \\\",\\\"8 min read\\\"]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h1\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"mt-1 text-2xl leading-tight sm:text-3xl\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Web Scraping with Playwright and Node.js: A Practical Tutorials\\\"}]]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"article\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"prose max-w-none prose-headings:text-ink prose-p:text-ink/80 prose-a:text-clay prose-strong:text-ink prose-code:text-clay prose-code:before:content-none prose-code:after:content-none\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"$11\\\"}}]]}]\\nd:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",\\\"0\\\",{\\\"name\\\":\\\"viewport\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",\\\"1\\\",{\\\"charSet\\\":\\\"utf-8\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"title\\\",\\\"2\\\",{\\\"children\\\":\\\"Abdihamid Moallim\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",\\\"3\\\",{\\\"name\\\":\\\"description\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"Software engineer. Building web apps, internal tools, and AI-backed products.\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"link\\\",\\\"4\\\",{\\\"rel\\\":\\\"icon\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/favicon.ico\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"image/x-icon\\\",\\\"sizes\\\":\\\"150x150\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"link\\\",\\\"5\\\",{\\\"rel\\\":\\\"icon\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/icon.png?02db24294edd3330\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"image/png\\\",\\\"sizes\\\":\\\"150x150\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",\\\"6\\\",{\\\"name\\\":\\\"next-size-adjust\\\"}]]\\n6:null\\n\"])</script></body></html>","rsc":"3:I[4707,[],\"\"]\n5:I[6423,[],\"\"]\n6:I[8003,[\"310\",\"static/chunks/0e5ce63c-87c8b437464bdc9c.js\",\"972\",\"static/chunks/972-0fea25be27918f94.js\",\"566\",\"static/chunks/566-a97c572560d10c0d.js\",\"185\",\"static/chunks/app/layout-04e2ba14e7dea6d8.js\"],\"\"]\n7:I[432,[\"310\",\"static/chunks/0e5ce63c-87c8b437464bdc9c.js\",\"972\",\"static/chunks/972-0fea25be27918f94.js\",\"566\",\"static/chunks/566-a97c572560d10c0d.js\",\"185\",\"static/chunks/app/layout-04e2ba14e7dea6d8.js\"],\"default\"]\n4:[\"slug\",\"web-scraping-playwright-node\",\"d\"]\n0:[\"1Xm8IygbKflRaIxtjQjqr\",[[[\"\",{\"children\":[\"blog\",{\"children\":[[\"slug\",\"web-scraping-playwright-node\",\"d\"],{\"children\":[\"__PAGE__?{\\\"slug\\\":\\\"web-scraping-playwright-node\\\"}\",{}]}]}]},\"$undefined\",\"$undefined\",true],[\"\",{\"children\":[\"blog\",{\"children\":[[\"slug\",\"web-scraping-playwright-node\",\"d\"],{\"children\":[\"__PAGE__\",{},[[\"$L1\",\"$L2\",null],null],null]},[null,[\"$\",\"$L3\",null,{\"parallelRouterKey\":\"children\",\"segmentPath\":[\"children\",\"blog\",\"children\",\"$4\",\"children\"],\"error\":\"$undefined\",\"errorStyles\":\"$undefined\",\"errorScripts\":\"$undefined\",\"template\":[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{}],\"templateStyles\":\"$undefined\",\"templateScripts\":\"$undefined\",\"notFound\":\"$undefined\",\"notFoundStyles\":\"$undefined\"}]],null]},[null,[\"$\",\"$L3\",null,{\"parallelRouterKey\":\"children\",\"segmentPath\":[\"children\",\"blog\",\"children\"],\"error\":\"$undefined\",\"errorStyles\":\"$undefined\",\"errorScripts\":\"$undefined\",\"template\":[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{}],\"templateStyles\":\"$undefined\",\"templateScripts\":\"$undefined\",\"notFound\":\"$undefined\",\"notFoundStyles\":\"$undefined\"}]],null]},[[[[\"$\",\"link\",\"0\",{\"rel\":\"stylesheet\",\"href\":\"/_next/static/css/f7c0bb5f82096374.css\",\"precedence\":\"next\",\"crossOrigin\":\"$undefined\"}]],[\"$\",\"html\",null,{\"lang\":\"en\",\"className\":\"__variable_f367f3 __variable_3c557b __variable_814fbd\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"head\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L6\",null,{\"async\":true,\"src\":\"https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtag/js?id=G-ZBHQKS3HR1\"}],[\"$\",\"$L6\",null,{\"id\":\"google-analytics\",\"strategy\":\"afterInteractive\",\"children\":\"\\n            window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];\\n            function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}\\n            gtag('js', new Date());\\n            gtag('config', 'G-ZBHQKS3HR1');\\n          \"}]]}],[\"$\",\"body\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L7\",null,{}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"pt-14\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L3\",null,{\"parallelRouterKey\":\"children\",\"segmentPath\":[\"children\"],\"error\":\"$undefined\",\"errorStyles\":\"$undefined\",\"errorScripts\":\"$undefined\",\"template\":[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{}],\"templateStyles\":\"$undefined\",\"templateScripts\":\"$undefined\",\"notFound\":[[\"$\",\"title\",null,{\"children\":\"404: This page could not be found.\"}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"style\":{\"fontFamily\":\"system-ui,\\\"Segoe UI\\\",Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif,\\\"Apple Color Emoji\\\",\\\"Segoe UI Emoji\\\"\",\"height\":\"100vh\",\"textAlign\":\"center\",\"display\":\"flex\",\"flexDirection\":\"column\",\"alignItems\":\"center\",\"justifyContent\":\"center\"},\"children\":[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"style\",null,{\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"body{color:#000;background:#fff;margin:0}.next-error-h1{border-right:1px solid rgba(0,0,0,.3)}@media (prefers-color-scheme:dark){body{color:#fff;background:#000}.next-error-h1{border-right:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.3)}}\"}}],[\"$\",\"h1\",null,{\"className\":\"next-error-h1\",\"style\":{\"display\":\"inline-block\",\"margin\":\"0 20px 0 0\",\"padding\":\"0 23px 0 0\",\"fontSize\":24,\"fontWeight\":500,\"verticalAlign\":\"top\",\"lineHeight\":\"49px\"},\"children\":\"404\"}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"style\":{\"display\":\"inline-block\"},\"children\":[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"style\":{\"fontSize\":14,\"fontWeight\":400,\"lineHeight\":\"49px\",\"margin\":0},\"children\":\"This page could not be found.\"}]}]]}]}]],\"notFoundStyles\":[]}],[\"$\",\"footer\",null,{\"className\":\"border-t border-ink/10 py-6\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"mx-auto flex max-w-6xl flex-col items-center justify-between gap-3 px-4 text-sm text-ink/50 sm:flex-row sm:px-6\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":[\"© \",2026,\" Abdihamid Moallim\"]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-4\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"a\",\"LinkedIn\",{\"href\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/abmoallim/\",\"target\":\"_blank\",\"rel\":\"noopener noreferrer\",\"className\":\"transition-colors hover:text-clay\",\"children\":\"LinkedIn\"}],[\"$\",\"a\",\"GitHub\",{\"href\":\"https://github.com/abmoallim\",\"target\":\"_blank\",\"rel\":\"noopener noreferrer\",\"className\":\"transition-colors hover:text-clay\",\"children\":\"GitHub\"}],[\"$\",\"a\",\"X\",{\"href\":\"https://x.com/abmoallim\",\"target\":\"_blank\",\"rel\":\"noopener noreferrer\",\"className\":\"transition-colors hover:text-clay\",\"children\":\"X\"}]]}]]}]}]]}]]}]]}]],null],null],[\"$L8\",null]]]]\n9:I[2972,[\"972\",\"static/chunks/972-0fea25be27918f94.js\",\"308\",\"static/chunks/app/blog/%5Bslug%5D/page-509dcbc32cb4be24.js\"],\"\"]\na:T1785,<p><img src=\"/imgs/web-scraping.png\" alt=\"alt text\">\nWeb scraping is an essential technique in a developer's toolkit, allowing the extraction of data from websites for various purposes, such as data analysis, monitoring, and automation. Playwright, paired with Node.js, provides a powerful and flexible framework for web scraping, especially when dealing with modern, dynamic websites. In this tutorial, we'll walk you through setting up a web scraping project with Playwright and cover essential aspects of scraping, from basic setups to handling more complex scenarios.</p>\n<h3>1. Setting Up Your Environment</h3>\n<p>To begin, you'll need to have Node.js installed on your machine. Node.js is a JavaScript runtime that allows you to run JavaScript code outside of a web browser. Once you have Node.js installed, you can create a new project directory and initialize a Node.js project:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">mkdir playwright-scraper\ncd playwright-scraper\nnpm init -y\nnpm install playwright\n</code></pre>\n<p>The commands above will create a new directory, initialize a Node.js project, and install Playwright. Playwright is a Node.js library to automate Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit with a single API. It is ideal for scraping tasks because of its ability to handle complex web interactions, including those involving JavaScript and dynamic content.</p>\n<h3>2. Writing Your First Playwright Script</h3>\n<p>Let's start by writing a simple script that launches a browser, navigates to a webpage, and retrieves the page title. Create a new file named <code>scraper.js</code> and add the following code:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-javascript\">const { chromium } = require('playwright');\n\n(async () => {\n  const browser = await chromium.launch();\n  const page = await browser.newPage();\n  await page.goto('https://example.com');\n  const title = await page.title();\n  console.log(`Title: ${title}`);\n  await browser.close();\n})();\n</code></pre>\n<p>In this script, we use Playwright to launch a Chromium browser, open a new page, navigate to \"<a href=\"https://example.com\">https://example.com</a>\", and print the page's title to the console. Finally, the browser is closed. This is a basic example, but it showcases the simplicity and power of Playwright for web scraping.</p>\n<h3>3. Extracting Data from a Web Page</h3>\n<p>Web scraping often involves extracting specific pieces of data from a webpage. Let's modify our script to extract the headlines from the Hacker News homepage. Update your <code>scraper.js</code> file with the following code:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-javascript\">await page.goto('https://news.ycombinator.com/');\nconst headlines = await page.$$eval('.storylink', links => links.map(link => link.textContent));\nconsole.log(headlines);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Here, we're using the <code>$$eval</code> function, which allows us to select all elements matching a CSS selector (<code>.storylink</code> in this case) and run a function on them. The function extracts the text content of each element and returns it as an array of strings.</p>\n<h3>4. Handling Dynamic Content</h3>\n<p>Modern websites often load content dynamically using JavaScript, which means that the content may not be available immediately when the page loads. Playwright's <code>waitForSelector</code> method can be used to wait for specific elements to appear before interacting with them:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-javascript\">await page.goto('https://example.com');\nawait page.waitForSelector('.dynamic-content');\nconst content = await page.$eval('.dynamic-content', el => el.textContent);\nconsole.log(content);\n</code></pre>\n<p>In this example, we wait for an element with the class <code>.dynamic-content</code> to appear on the page before extracting its text content.</p>\n<h3>5. Managing Authentication</h3>\n<p>Some websites require users to log in before accessing certain data. Playwright can handle this by filling out login forms and submitting them:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-javascript\">await page.goto('https://example.com/login');\nawait page.fill('#username', 'yourUsername');\nawait page.fill('#password', 'yourPassword');\nawait page.click('#loginButton');\n</code></pre>\n<p>This script navigates to a login page, fills out the username and password fields, and clicks the login button. Playwright will manage the session automatically, allowing you to scrape protected content.</p>\n<h3>6. Saving Scraped Data</h3>\n<p>Once you've extracted data from a webpage, you'll often want to save it for later use. You can save data to a JSON file using Node.js's built-in <code>fs</code> module:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-javascript\">const fs = require('fs');\nfs.writeFileSync('headlines.json', JSON.stringify(headlines, null, 2));\n</code></pre>\n<p>This code saves the <code>headlines</code> array to a file named <code>headlines.json</code>, formatting the JSON with an indentation of 2 spaces.</p>\n<h3>7. Best Practices for Web Scraping</h3>\n<p>When scraping websites, it's important to follow best practices to avoid legal issues or being blocked by the website. Here are some tips:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Respect <code>robots.txt</code>:</strong> Always check the site's <code>robots.txt</code> file to see what parts of the site you're allowed to scrape.</li>\n<li><strong>Rate Limiting:</strong> Introduce delays between requests to avoid overwhelming the server.</li>\n<li><strong>Error Handling:</strong> Implement error handling to manage issues such as network errors or unexpected changes in the webpage structure.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>Web scraping with Playwright and Node.js offers a powerful way to collect data from websites, whether they are static or dynamically loaded. With the basics covered in this tutorial, you should be well-equipped to start building your own web scrapers. From handling simple HTML pages to complex, JavaScript-heavy sites requiring authentication, Playwright provides the tools you need to get the job done efficiently.</p>\n<p>Happy scraping!</p>\n2:[\"$\",\"main\",null,{\"className\":\"mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-6 px-4 pb-8 pt-10 sm:px-6\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L9\",null,{\"href\":\"/blog\",\"className\":\"inline-block font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-ink/50 transition-colors hover:text-clay\",\"children\":\"← Back to writing\"}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-ink/40\",\"children\":[\"2024-08-24\",\" · \",\"8 min read\"]}],[\"$\",\"h1\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-2xl leading-tight sm:text-3xl\",\"children\":\"Web Scraping with Playwright and Node.js: A Practical Tutorials\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"article\",null,{\"className\":\"prose max-w-none prose-headings:text-ink prose-p:text-ink/80 prose-a:text-clay prose-strong:text-ink prose-code:text-clay prose-code:before:content-none prose-code:after:content-none\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"$a\"}}]]}]\n8:[[\"$\",\"meta\",\"0\",{\"name\":\"viewport\",\"content\":\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"1\",{\"charSet\":\"utf-8\"}],[\"$\",\"title\",\"2\",{\"children\":\"Abdihamid Moallim\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"3\",{\"name\":\"description\",\"content\":\"Software engineer. Building web apps, internal tools, and AI-backed products.\"}],[\"$\",\"link\",\"4\",{\"rel\":\"icon\",\"href\":\"/favicon.ico\",\"type\":\"image/x-icon\",\"sizes\":\"150x150\"}],[\"$\",\"link\",\"5\",{\"rel\":\"icon\",\"href\":\"/icon.png?02db24294edd3330\",\"type\":\"image/png\",\"sizes\":\"150x150\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"6\",{\"name\":\"next-size-adjust\"}]]\n1:null\n"}